[Guest]: Do this

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:29.440
[Guest]: And

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:30.440
[Guest]: We must

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:31.440
[Guest]: We need

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:32.440
[Guest]: To

00:20:32.440 --> 00:20:33.440
[Guest]: Act

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:34.440
[Guest]: Now

00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:35.440
[Guest]: And

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:36.440
[Guest]: We must

00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:37.440
[Guest]: Act

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:38.440
[Guest]: Now

00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:42.960
[Guest]: and you know you have to really like invest your time and I would like pick jobs that

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:47.760
[Guest]: would allow me to like leave early at 7.30ish and then run to a mic and do one or two open

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:48.760
[Guest]: mics in the evening.

00:20:48.760 --> 00:20:52.400
[Guest]: So every night I would go and I would do this material about what's it like coming out you

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:57.720
[Guest]: know and one advice I got as a comic was to stick to the material I'm doing for the first

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:04.080
[Guest]: six months, do that same four minutes everywhere so you can understand how that evolves automatically,

00:21:04.080 --> 00:21:06.640
[Guest]: what funny bits remain and stuff like that.

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:11.360
[Guest]: And for the first six months I was mainly bombing with that material you know so it

00:21:11.360 --> 00:21:16.200
[Guest]: became very difficult for me to like get spots and stuff like that and a lot of older comics

00:21:16.200 --> 00:21:21.480
[Guest]: like Sapan Verma, Kunal Kamra and Zakir and Biswa would advise me to stick to it you know

00:21:21.480 --> 00:21:24.600
[Guest]: don't don't change the narrative just because some jokes are not working because you have

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:29.320
[Guest]: a really strong idea of how you want to build this material.

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:33.040
[Guest]: So I would do that so from there it became easier for me to like channel my energy into

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:37.760
[Guest]: writing better material and you know you transition from the four minute phase to six minutes

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:40.160
[Guest]: and eight minutes and then 15 and stuff like that.

00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:44.080
[Guest]: So I was working at Hive, I was writing comedy, I was doing some writing work on the side

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:45.080
[Guest]: as well.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:49.200
[Guest]: All of this was going well and I was creating queer content so to say on my own.

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:54.120
[Guest]: We would do a small mic called the rainbow mic in Hive which was like calling all the

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.760
[Guest]: queer contestants to come and do whatever they wanted.

00:21:56.760 --> 00:22:04.400
[Guest]: Some would like recite poetry, storytelling, dancing, you know slam poetry, comedy as well.

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:08.600
[Guest]: So all kinds of queer performers were given a chance to like do their work.

00:22:08.600 --> 00:22:12.280
[Guest]: So that's when I found like oh my god there's an entire little undercircuit that we're building

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:15.960
[Guest]: and we're not even realizing that this is a movement on its own you know.

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:19.720
[Guest]: And there was not much happening as I said there was like always the gay party scene

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:24.500
[Guest]: but culturally for like the queers in Bombay and other metropolitan cities not much was

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:27.280
[Guest]: happening as much as I wanted to you know see.

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:31.700
[Guest]: So we were doing the small little thing and from there I began again like you know questioning

00:22:31.700 --> 00:22:35.960
[Guest]: whether like sooner or later will they find out because I now had half an hour of material

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:38.920
[Guest]: about coming out and my friends and homophobic.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:40.800
[Amit Varma]: And was any of it on YouTube or anything?

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:41.800
[Amit Varma]: Not yet.

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:45.040
[Guest]: There was only like some bits of it like here and there.

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:48.480
[Guest]: Somebody lost my footage also which was I think thankful because back then I was not

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:51.240
[Guest]: ready for that footage to come out.

00:22:51.240 --> 00:22:56.520
[Guest]: And there was another comic called Nick Pillow who's a white guy who's been teaching drama

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.040
[Guest]: in Bombay for the longest time.

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:00.440
[Guest]: So somebody told me he's also a queer comic.

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:06.440
[Guest]: So we came together and did a show called Homo's Odyssey which again a pun on Homo's

00:23:06.440 --> 00:23:07.440
[Guest]: Odyssey.

00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:08.440
[Guest]: You like puns.

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:09.440
[Guest]: I love puns.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:14.080
[Guest]: And so Homo's Odyssey became like this one two person show where you know do a lot of

00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:19.240
[Guest]: little acts together like we would do small sketches interspersed with a stand up as well.

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:21.800
[Guest]: And might I say the first stand up comedy kiss on stage.

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:22.800
[Unknown]: Oh wow.

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:23.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:25.800
[Guest]: We do have photos to prove but we can't put it online.

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:27.600
[Guest]: But we went there.

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:31.760
[Guest]: We actually wanted to like you know take it a little more like how much can people see

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:34.240
[Guest]: two men kissing on stage and be uncomfortable.

00:23:34.240 --> 00:23:35.600
[Guest]: That sort of stuff.

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:37.360
[Guest]: And then Nick moved on with his life.

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:39.440
[Guest]: He's now engaged and going to get married.

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:41.960
[Guest]: And then I was like okay now I have to do my show.

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:44.160
[Guest]: I have to still proceed with my material.

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:49.000
[Guest]: And I ended up doing Coming Out Soon which was a trial show.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:53.440
[Amit Varma]: And that was like again which morphed into The Good Child which I saw last week.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:58.200
[Guest]: But throughout this I remember Sharon who's the co-founder of The Hive and now Ku Klub.

00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:01.280
[Guest]: I was talking to her and she's like you know what dude two years of comedy and you've been

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:03.760
[Guest]: doing so much work with the LGBT stuff.

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:04.760
[Guest]: When will you tell your parents?

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:06.760
[Guest]: And I'm like that's a legit question Sharon.

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:09.280
[Guest]: I can't I can't imagine.

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:12.560
[Guest]: And hence like as I told you like I had to come out on different levels.

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:16.960
[Guest]: So after engineering I quit and became a writer and then after that I became an atheist as

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:18.080
[Guest]: I told you.

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:22.520
[Guest]: So there were already like too many blows I was giving out to my family which was staunchly

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:23.520
[Amit Varma]: conservative.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:24.520
[Amit Varma]: Like both my sisters are married.

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:25.520
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about these different blows.

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:26.520
[Guest]: How did they go down?

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:33.080
[Guest]: Like always like dramatically like it's it's not easy like I remember the way I left L&T

00:24:33.080 --> 00:24:35.520
[Guest]: was like which the company I was hired to work for.

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:36.520
[Amit Varma]: You're an engineer.

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:37.520
[Guest]: I'm an engineer.

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:39.600
[Guest]: Telecom engineer by qualification.

00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:44.600
[Guest]: But I got placed in Larsen and Toubro Infotech which is IT and I don't know IT.

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:48.720
[Guest]: And they're trying to like teach me programming and coding and I'm just dyslexic when it comes

00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:50.220
[Unknown]: to like coding.

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:51.440
[Guest]: So I left after two weeks.

00:24:51.440 --> 00:24:57.240
[Guest]: I still got a small paycheck and I was like I came home and mom's like tomorrow what time

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.240
[Guest]: do you have to go to work?

00:24:58.240 --> 00:24:59.240
[Guest]: I'm like I'm not going.

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:00.240
[Guest]: She's like why?

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:01.240
[Guest]: I'm like I just quit.

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:02.880
[Guest]: I did not want to do this.

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:07.920
[Guest]: And then just like became like an entire silent period for my father was like no talking for

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:12.520
[Guest]: three months and just like cold hearted like you know stone cold treatment.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:16.040
[Guest]: And mom was still like have you figured out what you want to do and all that.

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:22.440
[Guest]: And I remember the last day of not the last day but like they had to give us a test to

00:25:22.440 --> 00:25:27.680
[Guest]: pass us and see how we can fare for three months and then they give us jobs right.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:31.320
[Guest]: So when everybody else was studying I was sitting and writing a poem which I called

00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:33.320
[Guest]: across the bridge which was like a very metaphorical.

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:34.720
[Amit Varma]: Did you have it on you?

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:35.720
[Guest]: I do.

00:25:35.720 --> 00:25:36.720
[Guest]: One second.

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:41.480
[Guest]: So this is a very rhyme to rhyme kind of poem but here's what it says.

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:44.160
[Guest]: There's a boat in the river at the edge of the ridge.

00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:47.320
[Guest]: The boatman beckons to take you across the bridge.

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:48.480
[Guest]: You've heard about the other side.

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:49.800
[Guest]: You know it's bright and lovely.

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:53.740
[Guest]: You stand at the edge and ponder if it's worth being sad and lonely.

00:25:53.740 --> 00:25:54.740
[Guest]: You make a decision.

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.120
[Guest]: You take the leap.

00:25:56.120 --> 00:25:57.120
[Guest]: You land on the boat.

00:25:57.120 --> 00:25:58.680
[Guest]: The edge though steep.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:25:59.680
[Guest]: The currents are strong.

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:01.040
[Guest]: The journey is tough.

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:02.040
[Guest]: The water is coarse.

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:03.040
[Guest]: It's choppy.

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:04.040
[Guest]: It's rough.

00:26:04.040 --> 00:26:05.040
[Guest]: You're scared to cross.

00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:06.400
[Guest]: Now you risk a glance.

00:26:06.400 --> 00:26:09.080
[Guest]: Your friends and family say you've missed your chance.

00:26:09.080 --> 00:26:13.680
[Guest]: The chance to stick to the regular show, the chance to be ordinary and cheat your core.

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:16.200
[Guest]: The belief it surges and so does the wave.

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:17.200
[Guest]: You don't need to look back.

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:18.720
[Guest]: You're far too brave.

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:19.720
[Guest]: The storm descends.

00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:20.960
[Guest]: The boat sails calm.

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:21.960
[Guest]: The bridge it passes.

00:26:21.960 --> 00:26:23.840
[Guest]: You're befuddled with charm.

00:26:23.840 --> 00:26:24.840
[Guest]: The other shore arrives.

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:26.080
[Guest]: You begin to strut.

