[Amit Varma]: He just like he goes into his whole...

00:38:16.680 --> 00:38:17.680
[Amit Varma]: He wouldn't talk to you.

00:38:17.680 --> 00:38:22.280
[Guest]: Like he goes into a gargoyle mode where he just like ignores my existence altogether.

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:25.360
[Guest]: And like, again, all the talking happens to my mother, right?

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:30.160
[Guest]: And hence when, like when I came out, he was again like not understanding.

00:38:30.160 --> 00:38:36.280
[Guest]: So I used Aamir Khan's Satyamev Jayate episode on LGBT rights to show it to them that, hey,

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.840
[Guest]: there are more people like me, watch this video, Aamir Khan's cool about it.

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:41.840
[Guest]: So why can't you be cool about it?

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:46.280
[Guest]: So that weekend, that Saturday or Sunday, I showed them the video, and then they softened

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:47.720
[Guest]: up a little bit.

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:53.120
[Guest]: So a whole week of like, softened up as in, they're like, yeah, it's okay, dad, you're

00:38:53.120 --> 00:38:54.120
[Guest]: okay.

00:38:54.120 --> 00:38:55.120
[Guest]: They finally said that line.

00:38:55.120 --> 00:38:58.360
[Guest]: Like, you know, we understand it's okay, but don't do something wrong, was the idea.

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:01.960
[Guest]: Because my mom was like, okay, there's still people who are gay, just immediately they

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:02.960
[Guest]: have AIDS.

00:39:02.960 --> 00:39:03.960
[Unknown]: Like, that's how it works.

00:39:03.960 --> 00:39:04.960
[Guest]: I'm like, no.

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:08.600
[Guest]: But then you have to, again, pick your battles every day, one at a time.

00:39:08.600 --> 00:39:12.920
[Guest]: And I decided to come out first and then talk about the other stuff in life.

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:15.440
[Amit Varma]: In some sense, I mean, I mean, you spoke about this a lot.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:19.160
[Amit Varma]: And it was the whole narrative was very moving in the show that you did The Good Child.

00:39:19.160 --> 00:39:23.760
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that kind of struck me there was that, you know, up till this

00:39:23.760 --> 00:39:26.800
[Amit Varma]: point, you could say your parents brought you up, but now suddenly you were bringing

00:39:26.800 --> 00:39:32.800
[Amit Varma]: them up by revealing all these aspects of yourselves and forcing them to grow, to kind

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:36.280
[Amit Varma]: of accept you as you are.

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:39.480
[Guest]: And a lot of growing up happens between these conversations.

00:39:39.480 --> 00:39:44.040
[Guest]: Because around the same time, my mom's main, you know, concern that year was that while

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:49.080
[Guest]: I came out to her, my sister, who also had an autistic kid was diagnosed autistic that

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:50.080
[Guest]: year.

00:39:50.080 --> 00:39:55.080
[Guest]: So it was like a double blow, she felt almost like, you know, and in a very weird way, like,

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:59.400
[Guest]: my sister's kids, autism kind of helped her cope with the fact that, hey, I did not have

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:03.800
[Guest]: a choice in how I chose my orientation, because the kid did not choose how he would have a

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:05.440
[Guest]: social anxiety in life.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:09.960
[Guest]: You know, like, so even though it's weird that it's a it's a mental illness, and orientation

00:40:09.960 --> 00:40:15.080
[Guest]: is not the same, you know, not the same level, I still choose to be like, hey, at least it's

00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:18.840
[Guest]: helping her understand and deal with it, you know, you can be very politically correct

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:22.640
[Guest]: at the same time with your parents, because there's always going to be some level of weirdness

00:40:22.640 --> 00:40:23.640
[Guest]: to it.

00:40:23.640 --> 00:40:26.520
[Guest]: So I shave my face, she's like, you know what, I like you better with a beard, because that

00:40:26.520 --> 00:40:31.000
[Guest]: looks more manly on you, you look more effeminate, I'm like, Mom, how can you say such amazing

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.040
[Guest]: things and weird things at the same time?

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.040
[Guest]: That's how mothers are.

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:38.020
[Guest]: They are just like, they're concerned about you, but they'll take it in their stride eventually

00:40:38.020 --> 00:40:41.380
[Guest]: by just like letting them love you for who you are again.

00:40:41.380 --> 00:40:46.680
[Guest]: So that's, that's my main point that if you don't stop pretending, you'll never know how

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:49.480
[Amit Varma]: your family is going to like you and you know,

00:40:49.480 --> 00:40:53.400
[Amit Varma]: And does that normalcy extend to for example, like, have you ever taken any of the men you

00:40:53.400 --> 00:40:58.560
[Amit Varma]: were dating home or any of your gay activist friends and you know, how does the family

00:40:58.560 --> 00:40:59.560
[Guest]: react to that?

00:40:59.560 --> 00:41:02.880
[Guest]: Well, I've met some of my gay friends, but I've never brought anybody home.

00:41:02.880 --> 00:41:05.240
[Guest]: I think they're still a little far away.

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:09.040
[Guest]: And like, they know that I'm doing comedy and I talk about this and I give interviews

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:12.080
[Guest]: and it's all over the newsletter.

00:41:12.080 --> 00:41:16.880
[Guest]: So they know for a fact that there's some level of publicity that goes with my work.

00:41:16.880 --> 00:41:21.880
[Guest]: And I think it's okay, because I tell them I'm doing it for the right reasons, you know.

00:41:21.880 --> 00:41:28.840
[Guest]: And eventually, my mom and I do talk about like, when I'm going out with like, you know,

00:41:28.840 --> 00:41:32.960
[Guest]: what's it like to have lived inside the closet and outside the closet, and this whole conversation

00:41:32.960 --> 00:41:34.520
[Guest]: goes on for a while.

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:40.200
[Guest]: But I'm still not like seriously going to take her to meet a guy I'm dating and vice

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:41.200
[Amit Varma]: versa.

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, for a gay person, as opposed to a straight person, the process of finding

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:48.840
[Amit Varma]: love is very difficult, finding love, finding companionship, and so on, you know, straight

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:52.840
[Amit Varma]: men do it through, you know, whatever the normal socializing you do, and you like someone

00:41:52.840 --> 00:41:54.680
[Amit Varma]: and you hit on them.

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And if it's Bollywood, then you EFTs them till they give in.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:03.380
[Amit Varma]: But for someone like you, it's a very fraught process, because you might keep bumping into

00:42:03.380 --> 00:42:05.160
[Amit Varma]: homophobia in different places.

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, how did that kind of process work out where you start, where you start

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:14.720
[Amit Varma]: finding companionship and that kind of friendship?

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:19.320
[Guest]: So there's obviously online dating, which has helped a lot of people meet cool people

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:21.040
[Guest]: around the world.

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:26.800
[Guest]: And that's what I found, like, my past relationships have been of three different apps.

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:30.560
[Guest]: So that way, I've been like meeting enough number of people overall.

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:34.320
[Guest]: In fact, I made like a list for my ex when I was dating him that these are the men I've

00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:37.760
[Guest]: slept with in my past and beyond this, there won't be anybody else but you.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:38.760
[Unknown]: Wow.

00:42:38.760 --> 00:42:42.360
[Guest]: Very naive move because there was the list continues to this day.

00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:48.560
[Guest]: But you know, I tell every new lover, I do I do I'm very on the face sort of because

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:51.840
[Guest]: like it is like when you're going to the whole world of gay dating.

00:42:51.840 --> 00:42:54.920
[Guest]: It's very easy to get sex because it's just like it's that easy.

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:57.760
[Guest]: It's like, you know, nobody knows no one keeps a track of it.

00:42:57.760 --> 00:43:01.640
[Guest]: The thrill of it is what actually excites a lot of people like it's all behind closed

00:43:01.640 --> 00:43:02.840
[Guest]: doors and everything.

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:04.360
[Guest]: So it's easy to get laid.

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:07.600
[Guest]: But then when someone says translate this love outside where you can walk on the street

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:11.320
[Guest]: on the pavement with your partner's hand in your hand, or you know, go on dates and stuff

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:14.880
[Guest]: like that, it immediately becomes a problem because then you're acting like two bros on

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:19.280
[Guest]: a date who won't sit on the same side of the table, won't feed each other, you know, the

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:23.520
[Guest]: cutesy things you want to do because you have to, you have to act a certain way.

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:28.560
[Guest]: So again, like, you know, this happened because as soon as you want to show your love, it

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:30.640
[Guest]: becomes too cumbersome for some people.

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:33.880
[Guest]: And that's how most relationships don't work out in the long run.

00:43:33.880 --> 00:43:38.600
[Guest]: People online will tell you that he's looking for hookups and not for like longevity.

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:42.320
[Guest]: And again, just like go from one guy to the other hoping that this one works out.

00:43:42.320 --> 00:43:44.560
[Guest]: So that was like for the longest time.

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:46.400
[Guest]: And I was very gullible in my early 20s.

00:43:46.400 --> 00:43:52.120
[Guest]: I feel like because I was so bought up on the idea for Mills and Boones-esque love story

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:56.560
[Guest]: where the whole world is like, you know, behind you and you're like riding on the beach with

00:43:56.560 --> 00:43:58.680
[Guest]: like a horse or whatever.

00:43:58.680 --> 00:44:04.880
[Amit Varma]: Not the guy, but riding on the beach with a horse and a guy.

00:44:04.880 --> 00:44:11.480
[Guest]: So I had a very, very rom-com-esque look at life and didn't work out really well because

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:15.120
[Guest]: nobody was willing to come out of the closet even like to meet me halfway.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:19.640
[Guest]: I think every woman is looking for a man like you who looks at the world like that.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:21.320
[Guest]: But yeah, eventually we all end up being jaded.

00:44:21.320 --> 00:44:22.320
[Guest]: So it's cool.

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:24.880
[Guest]: Like, you know, like right now at 26, 27, I'm like...

00:44:24.880 --> 00:44:27.960
[Amit Varma]: But are you jaded or when you meet the next man, will you again be a romantic?

00:44:27.960 --> 00:44:30.040
[Guest]: I am dating a very young kid right now.

00:44:30.040 --> 00:44:35.920
[Guest]: I'm dating a 20-year-old who used to stalk me before I got to know who he was.

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:39.840
[Guest]: Basically, he watched me live at a stand-up show and then was following up with my social

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:44.560
[Guest]: media work and then finally got the courage to say, hey, I like you and I met him and

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:46.160
[Guest]: it's kind of cute.

00:44:46.160 --> 00:44:47.200
[Guest]: So yeah.

00:44:47.200 --> 00:44:51.480
[Guest]: So it's like, you know, in a weird way, like I didn't have to resort to like online dating

00:44:51.480 --> 00:44:55.960
[Guest]: to find this person because they were already there in my life before I realized it, you

00:44:55.960 --> 00:44:56.960
[Guest]: know.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:45:02.440
[Guest]: And hence, it's cool to like go out and associate, go to parties and situations.

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:07.160
[Guest]: But again, my brand with parties, again, is that they all just like come together and

00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:08.320
[Guest]: couples have a good time.

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:12.440
[Guest]: But people who are looking for love or for sex that night end up meeting each other and

00:45:12.440 --> 00:45:14.880
[Guest]: hooking up for that one night.

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:19.000
[Guest]: And I sometimes end up being worried about like, what's the health situation?

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:24.200
[Guest]: And you don't know because you meet someone randomly and that night you will have sex.

00:45:24.200 --> 00:45:28.600
[Guest]: And a lot of people do not tell you about what their STD situation is.

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:29.600
[Guest]: And how do you know that?

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:31.720
[Guest]: So you have to like worry about that as well.

00:45:31.720 --> 00:45:34.880
[Guest]: So a lot of things go on in your mind when you're going out there, you know, it's not

00:45:34.880 --> 00:45:38.880
[Guest]: it's not just like, you go and meet the man of your dreams overnight.

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:43.560
[Guest]: It's a trial and error method and again, like get checked every two or three months.

00:45:43.560 --> 00:45:47.820
[Amit Varma]: So I think in around 2007, when I was writing a column for Mint, I'd written this piece

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:52.720
[Amit Varma]: called the Matunga racket, a friend of mine, Vikram doctor had put me on to something that

00:45:52.720 --> 00:45:57.560
[Amit Varma]: used to happen where cops would basically go online and they'd hook up with gay men

00:45:57.560 --> 00:46:01.800
[Unknown]: pretending to be a gay man themselves and call them to Matunga station.

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:05.640
[Amit Varma]: And when the person landed up in Matunga station, they'd grab him and take him to his ATM machine

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:11.960
[Amit Varma]: and take out whatever cash and basically blackmail the guy using 377 I mean, like all bad laws,

00:46:11.960 --> 00:46:14.320
[Guest]: it was a rent seeking mechanism for them.

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:15.720
[Guest]: Does that kind of thing still happen?

00:46:15.720 --> 00:46:16.720
[Guest]: It still happens.

00:46:16.720 --> 00:46:20.880
[Guest]: My friend who went to Delhi last week got extorted by two dudes.

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:25.220
[Guest]: Like even if it's not cops, it's other men only who are trying to run a racket on online.

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:29.960
[Guest]: And because section 377 is so highly spoken about, people use it all the time to extort

00:46:29.960 --> 00:46:33.520
[Guest]: money out of people and you know, they'll rob you, they'll beat you up, they'll go come

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:35.000
[Guest]: to your hotel room.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:39.120
[Guest]: Because again, like the trust factor is so weird on these online dating apps.

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:42.520
[Guest]: People don't show their face and you've seen me joke about that as well when I speak about

00:46:42.520 --> 00:46:47.000
[Guest]: Grindr is that like people do not want to show that they're gay on Grindr.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:50.640
[Guest]: And if that person is on Grindr, it's because they're gay, unless they're trying to extort

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:54.560
[Guest]: you and they can't extort you for being gay in this country, unless they catch you in

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:58.880
[Guest]: the act of carnal intercourse, there's no way they can send you to jail for being gay.

00:46:58.880 --> 00:47:01.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, you should really just brazen it out.

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:05.760
[Amit Varma]: But I think the main fear of most of the people who get caught is that their family will be

00:47:05.760 --> 00:47:07.400
[Amit Varma]: told they might not have come out.

00:47:07.400 --> 00:47:08.400
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:47:08.400 --> 00:47:11.800
[Guest]: But then again, that's the system it's feeding itself, you know, we don't come out because

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:15.120
[Guest]: we're scared about like what the society will say, society will say something because we're

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:16.120
[Guest]: not coming out.

00:47:16.120 --> 00:47:17.120
[Guest]: It's a vicious cycle of...

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:20.760
[Amit Varma]: If you just come out and you can do it fearlessly, then that's...

00:47:20.760 --> 00:47:21.760
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:47:21.760 --> 00:47:22.760
[Guest]: Then they won't say, oh, you're gay, I'll tell your family.

00:47:22.760 --> 00:47:23.760
[Guest]: Sure, go ahead.

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:25.800
[Guest]: I told my family before you, I beat you to it.

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:26.800
[Guest]: Give me money now.

00:47:26.800 --> 00:47:29.120
[Guest]: That's how you extort the money out of them.

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:33.760
[Guest]: I don't know, because I've found so much comfort in telling people that I can't imagine living

00:47:33.760 --> 00:47:35.400
[Guest]: that kind of suffocated life.

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:40.280
[Guest]: We're trying to like meet all your life's goals at the same time, worry about this constantly

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:44.040
[Guest]: that you can't tell your family or they'll find out someday and then how will they react.

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:48.920
[Guest]: Dealing with that guilt is so difficult sometimes that just saying it out loud helps you.

00:47:48.920 --> 00:47:52.360
[Guest]: This went out so much of the of the aggression that you've lived with your entire life, you

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:56.280
[Guest]: know, like with my mom at every stage in my life from the point I was 15 when I could

00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:58.580
[Guest]: like, you know, reaffirm my thoughts.

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:01.960
[Guest]: That thing was always there on my albums, I'd be like right here, I would hold on to

00:48:01.960 --> 00:48:02.960
[Guest]: it and not tell her.

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:07.800
[Guest]: And I just regret I had wish I told her earlier so everything that happened in my life afterwards

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:10.960
[Guest]: would have been much more easier to deal with, you know, I could have gone into the arts

00:48:10.960 --> 00:48:14.320
[Guest]: much easily instead of having to struggle and try to please them at every level.

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:18.500
[Guest]: That's what we're told as Indian kids, right, just please your parents at every level.

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:22.080
[Guest]: But if you just come out and be who you are, and just tell them like for the for the from

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:26.560
[Guest]: the very beginning that you do not care about the world's opinion, because you can do what

00:48:26.560 --> 00:48:28.660
[Guest]: you want to do in your life eventually.

00:48:28.660 --> 00:48:32.200
[Guest]: And who you want to do in your life eventually, you'll find that kind of happiness.

00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:36.700
[Guest]: And I think it's for everybody in this community to take that control of that life.

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:40.920
[Guest]: Because as soon as you let these powers extort you for something that's not wrong, then

00:48:40.920 --> 00:48:43.600
[Guest]: you yourself becoming a part of the problem, right?

00:48:43.600 --> 00:48:46.680
[Amit Varma]: Because you're allowing them to, you're allowing yourself to be a victim, basically, which

00:48:46.680 --> 00:48:47.680
[Guest]: you don't have to.

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:48.680
[Amit Varma]: You don't have to.

00:48:48.680 --> 00:48:49.680
[Amit Varma]: So I'm just thinking aloud here.

00:48:49.680 --> 00:48:54.480
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me that, you know, for for most of us, and certainly for me, sexuality is

00:48:54.480 --> 00:48:55.840
[Amit Varma]: something that is incidental.

00:48:55.840 --> 00:48:57.360
[Amit Varma]: I happen to be heterosexual.

00:48:57.360 --> 00:48:58.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's it.

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:00.600
[Amit Varma]: But it doesn't shape me in any other way than that.

00:49:00.600 --> 00:49:06.000
[Amit Varma]: But would it be the case that for for you and for maybe for other gay people, you know,

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:10.920
[Amit Varma]: that your sexuality does shape you in much deeper ways, because that whole struggle of

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:14.680
[Amit Varma]: coming to terms with what you are and bringing it out to the world consumes you and makes

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:16.360
[Amit Varma]: you who you are?

00:49:16.360 --> 00:49:20.720
[Guest]: It does, like almost every other gay friend I have, like has some level of social anxiety,

00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:25.640
[Guest]: they live with like depression and they self doubt a lot.

00:49:25.640 --> 00:49:31.320
[Guest]: You know, it's a very in depth problem because of like living with so much denial and you

00:49:31.320 --> 00:49:35.360
[Guest]: know, not being able to come out can do like a lot of things wrong for you.

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:38.680
[Guest]: Internally, because you just like end up crying every night.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:42.560
[Guest]: And I'm not even generalizing here, because I know a lot of friends who are going through

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:44.880
[Guest]: the same thing over and over again.

00:49:44.880 --> 00:49:48.200
[Guest]: Exactly why there's so many suicide cases and so many, like, you know, all these high

00:49:48.200 --> 00:49:52.480
[Guest]: fun situations happen because people push themselves and try to get the best out of

00:49:52.480 --> 00:49:58.160
[Guest]: life when they can't really put a label to it, you know, and that kind of lifestyle kind

00:49:58.160 --> 00:50:00.760
[Guest]: of ends up very tragically sometimes.

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:04.800
[Guest]: And at 17, I was very suicidal, I wanted to just like end my life and be done with it,

00:50:04.800 --> 00:50:06.840
[Guest]: it seemed like an easy option.

00:50:06.840 --> 00:50:12.000
[Guest]: So I think we have to talk about mental illness also very profoundly when it comes to gay

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:17.320
[Guest]: rights, because there's like a lot of extremism there as well, and we're not really controlling

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:19.560
[Guest]: it properly, you know.

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:26.080
[Guest]: And that's why I think a problem that is associated with coming out or with growing up gay is

00:50:26.080 --> 00:50:29.320
[Guest]: that you suppress so much to an extent that you use every kind of method to like deal

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:30.920
[Guest]: with that.

00:50:30.920 --> 00:50:36.920
[Guest]: And I've seen like, a lot of people in the community slowly, you know, giving up and

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:42.520
[Guest]: passing away in their own stride, you know, like how they ended their lives because they

00:50:42.520 --> 00:50:44.960
[Amit Varma]: could not deal with the worries of how the world is.

00:50:44.960 --> 00:50:48.880
[Amit Varma]: And the tragic part is that it's the fault of society or the state and whoever's fault

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:52.320
[Amit Varma]: it is, it's not their fault, they're victims.

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:56.760
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, every suicide is a murder in a manner of speaking.

00:50:56.760 --> 00:51:02.120
[Amit Varma]: Let's then you know, move on from here to talk about the LGBT community and I'm sort

00:51:02.120 --> 00:51:06.360
[Amit Varma]: of if I can show quote marks around the word community, because I often don't understand

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:07.360
[Amit Varma]: such terms.

00:51:07.360 --> 00:51:11.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the way I look at the world is we're all sort of just individuals.

00:51:11.160 --> 00:51:16.800
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, we form communities around our interests or our identities or whatever, but they don't.

00:51:16.800 --> 00:51:18.320
[Amit Varma]: What is this queer community?

00:51:18.320 --> 00:51:22.680
[Guest]: So queer community is mainly a stronghold for a lot of people, because, as I said, like

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:26.960
[Guest]: a lot of parents do not accept their kids as they are, so they find their own families.

00:51:26.960 --> 00:51:29.840
[Guest]: And hence the need for a queer community to be born.

00:51:29.840 --> 00:51:35.520
[Guest]: Because if it dates back to the American Stonewall period, right, where a lot of people would

00:51:35.520 --> 00:51:37.400
[Guest]: come together and party.

00:51:37.400 --> 00:51:41.680
[Guest]: And even though they had varied interests, for example, some had drag queens coming in,

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:46.640
[Guest]: some had like lesbian butch women coming in, some had gay men coming into like hookup.

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:50.400
[Guest]: The normalcy was found that they were all the same kind of heathens, right?

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:54.600
[Guest]: And hence they would come together and party and they would like try to, again, back in

00:51:54.600 --> 00:51:59.480
[Guest]: the day, extort money, cops would charge in on them, the Stonewall riots happened.

00:51:59.480 --> 00:52:03.720
[Guest]: And like any riot that happens because of a community is because of the understanding

00:52:03.720 --> 00:52:06.520
[Guest]: that they've all suffered from the same problems.

00:52:06.520 --> 00:52:13.080
[Guest]: And if you were like a black lesbian, back in the 50s, you were already down the drain

00:52:13.080 --> 00:52:17.160
[Guest]: because you were like, the lowest rung when it comes to understanding, if you're a white

00:52:17.160 --> 00:52:19.200
[Guest]: gay man, you still have some privilege.

00:52:19.200 --> 00:52:23.480
[Guest]: But if you're a black lesbian woman, you have a different kind of privilege, which is not

00:52:23.480 --> 00:52:24.680
[Guest]: afforded to you.

00:52:24.680 --> 00:52:27.800
[Guest]: So for them, fighting the supreme power became like a common thing.

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:33.640
[Guest]: And hence, the LGBT community around the world is fighting the same thing, finding the commonness

00:52:33.640 --> 00:52:38.960
[Guest]: in being who you are at the same time, also finding love and acceptance within the community.

00:52:38.960 --> 00:52:44.320
[Amit Varma]: And now it's where it is like, you know, it's a community, therefore, which is born not

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:50.800
[Amit Varma]: out of the identity you're born into, but it's a community of choice and necessity.

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:52.960
[Guest]: And is it therefore stronger for that reason?

00:52:52.960 --> 00:52:57.040
[Guest]: It is because the commonness in the voice and the power with which the community hits

00:52:57.040 --> 00:53:00.560
[Guest]: back, because it does have the most creative individuals overall.

00:53:00.560 --> 00:53:04.320
[Guest]: And you know, if you look at the ad campaigns that have gone around the world in the past

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:09.160
[Guest]: few years, with regards to finding gay voices and giving them rights, you'll find a very

00:53:09.160 --> 00:53:13.080
[Guest]: innovative way of storytelling because it's not just about fighting for rights, but also

00:53:13.080 --> 00:53:16.560
[Guest]: about the right to love, right to like, you know, find the same kind of housing that everybody

00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:17.720
[Guest]: else has.

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:21.320
[Guest]: So when you look at it from an emotional level, gay marriage is making more sense, because

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:26.400
[Guest]: then if you can't live with the person you love the most, then how would you even live?

00:53:26.400 --> 00:53:31.560
[Guest]: And hence, the whole community became more stronger in the mid 2009 when Obama was like,

00:53:31.560 --> 00:53:36.480
[Guest]: you know, and believe it or not, like everywhere around the world, America does influence the

00:53:36.480 --> 00:53:40.400
[Guest]: thought pattern a lot when it comes to all the liberalist movements.

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:44.960
[Guest]: And so then when moved on to Europe as well, it became much easier for them to mimic these

00:53:44.960 --> 00:53:48.400
[Guest]: movements and you know, allow people to vote for the right thing.

00:53:48.400 --> 00:53:51.920
[Guest]: And if you look at like the ad campaign Ireland did to like get Paris to come out and vote

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:55.320
[Guest]: for their kids favour, because like, it's a matter of love.

00:53:55.320 --> 00:53:59.400
[Guest]: And when you boil it down to love, it's all kind of coming together already.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:06.080
[Guest]: So that's why the LGBT community has been ever inclusive, because now it's gone to QIA.

00:54:06.080 --> 00:54:11.200
[Guest]: And you know, intersex, asexual, queer couples are also like a part of the whole gamut now.

00:54:11.200 --> 00:54:14.960
[Guest]: And we are just getting to the tip of the iceberg now is what I mean.

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:20.520
[Guest]: And in India, how strong is it's pretty strong now, like in Bombay, and mainly metro cities

00:54:20.520 --> 00:54:25.160
[Guest]: like Delhi, Bangalore and Kolkata and Chennai.

00:54:25.160 --> 00:54:28.960
[Guest]: So they have like a lot of collectives coming together, a lot of people do a lot of different

00:54:28.960 --> 00:54:29.960
[Guest]: things.

00:54:29.960 --> 00:54:35.400
[Guest]: So people organize parties, some people do actual donation work, some people do research

00:54:35.400 --> 00:54:36.640
[Guest]: work.

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:41.000
[Guest]: And you have like eight centres to help people diagnose themselves.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.080
[Guest]: And research centres again for that very purpose.

00:54:43.080 --> 00:54:47.480
[Guest]: So a lot of things happening in Bombay, when you do the pride, like every year, the number

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:50.800
[Guest]: of people participating increases along with the allies.

00:54:50.800 --> 00:54:54.280
[Guest]: So from last year, it was 10,000, it went to 15,000 this year.

00:54:54.280 --> 00:54:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's growing every year.

00:54:55.760 --> 00:55:01.360
[Amit Varma]: I was struck by what you said earlier about how your first few relationships came by because

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:02.360
[Amit Varma]: of online dating.

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:06.880
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, the need for online dating, therefore seems to indicate that the natural

00:55:06.880 --> 00:55:11.880
[Amit Varma]: ecosystem within the real world where you meet other gay people simply wasn't that large.

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:15.280
[Amit Varma]: So you had to do online dating, that's the only way you could meet new people.

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:16.560
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that's changed?

00:55:16.560 --> 00:55:18.440
[Amit Varma]: Is the ecosystem larger?

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:23.040
[Amit Varma]: And very specifically, if say a young 17 year old or 18 year old gay person is listening

00:55:23.040 --> 00:55:26.640
[Amit Varma]: to this podcast right now, and he's like, I want to go out there and meet more people

00:55:26.640 --> 00:55:27.640
[Amit Varma]: like me.

00:55:27.640 --> 00:55:30.280
[Amit Varma]: What's he got to do?

00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:36.720
[Guest]: So you have to like look up the local, they have to basically look out for the local queer

00:55:36.720 --> 00:55:38.480
[Guest]: center that they can approach.

00:55:38.480 --> 00:55:43.400
[Guest]: If you're in Bombay, you have the Hamsafar Trust, which is in Wakola, they do a lot of

00:55:43.400 --> 00:55:47.720
[Guest]: community based fun open mics, and they do like a lot of Friday evening get togethers,

00:55:47.720 --> 00:55:51.280
[Guest]: while at the same time helping people get diagnosed and stuff like that, you know, so

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:56.120
[Guest]: like, you'll always have a lot of these queer centers and collectives and open mics and

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:57.720
[Guest]: activities to participate in.

00:55:57.720 --> 00:56:01.040
[Guest]: Don't go with the intention of hooking up to all of these, obviously, my whole thing

00:56:01.040 --> 00:56:04.840
[Guest]: is that first go and learn the community, understand, meet people, understand different

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:08.440
[Guest]: behaviors, lifestyles, and you know, explore that side of it.

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:13.040
[Guest]: And then if you meet someone organically amazing, there are parties that associate with just

00:56:13.040 --> 00:56:15.840
[Guest]: like getting you to drink and have a good time.

00:56:15.840 --> 00:56:17.960
[Guest]: And a lot of things happen at these parties.

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:20.920
[Guest]: If that's your thing, then be about 21 and then have a good time.

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:24.920
[Guest]: Don't be 17 and go to these parties, because then your image of the community will be different

00:56:24.920 --> 00:56:27.360
[Guest]: than what you have to perceive.

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:31.880
[Guest]: And go to a pride, go to a local bookstore, you'd say in a sense that you'd go to these

00:56:31.880 --> 00:56:35.480
[Amit Varma]: for the same reason that as a kid, you went to church to find that sense of community

00:56:35.480 --> 00:56:38.560
[Guest]: rather than, yes, you know, any specific.

00:56:38.560 --> 00:56:39.560
[Guest]: So in that way, nothing's changed.

00:56:39.560 --> 00:56:44.840
[Guest]: So you're still the altar boy, I'm still the altar boy, but this time on the other end

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:47.040
[Amit Varma]: of the spectrum.

00:56:47.040 --> 00:56:49.440
[Amit Varma]: And how has popular culture changed through this time?

00:56:49.440 --> 00:56:55.840
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, when you were a kid in the late 90s, early 2000s, like from whatever,

00:56:55.840 --> 00:57:01.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, and one thing that is pretty obvious about Bollywood is that it's a tokenism.

00:57:01.520 --> 00:57:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes they'll put a token gay out there, or sometimes they'll have a gay for comic

00:57:05.200 --> 00:57:10.880
[Amit Varma]: effect and, you know, just, you know, perpetuate all those harmful stereotypes.

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:16.960
[Amit Varma]: And it's very rare that they actually like some of the most beautiful movies I've seen

00:57:16.960 --> 00:57:22.880
[Amit Varma]: coming out of Hollywood in recent years, right from Brokeback Mountain to Moonlight, you

00:57:22.880 --> 00:57:29.400
[Amit Varma]: know, do show gay love in such a beautiful way, but they have, I mean, apart from maybe

00:57:29.400 --> 00:57:35.360
[Amit Varma]: I can offhand remember Kapoor and Sons, but how has popular culture adapted to this?

00:57:35.360 --> 00:57:39.440
[Guest]: Bollywood is still grasping, you know, at its kind of roots, because remember Dostana?

00:57:39.440 --> 00:57:44.000
[Guest]: Like, I remember Dostana happened at a very formative year in my life when I was like,

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:47.520
[Unknown]: still in the church trying to, you know, come out to my church friends.

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:51.440
[Guest]: But then we went to watch this movie at Gayety Galaxy together.

00:57:51.440 --> 00:57:54.480
[Guest]: And I was just like, very taken aback because I'm like, they're not even gay, they're just

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:55.600
[Amit Varma]: like pretending to be gay.

00:57:55.600 --> 00:57:57.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm just happy you didn't make a pun about Gayety Galaxy.

00:57:57.760 --> 00:57:58.760
[Guest]: Continue.

00:57:58.760 --> 00:57:59.760
[Guest]: Oh yeah.

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:00.760
[Guest]: You missed that.

00:58:00.760 --> 00:58:02.640
[Guest]: I'll let that go this time.

00:58:02.640 --> 00:58:07.800
[Guest]: But there is a magazine called Gayalaxy, by the way, it's a publication for the gays.

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:12.920
[Guest]: So they were all like enjoying the movie and I was like, this sounds so wrong as a movie.

00:58:12.920 --> 00:58:17.080
[Guest]: It's just like pandering and it's not actually talking about gay rights, it's just like two

00:58:17.080 --> 00:58:20.440
[Guest]: men acting gay to get a girl, that kind of stuff.

00:58:20.440 --> 00:58:22.680
[Guest]: So I would just like, let it go.

00:58:22.680 --> 00:58:28.260
[Guest]: And that's why when I was exposed to Western media, it was easier.

00:58:28.260 --> 00:58:32.160
[Guest]: So if you watch Will and Grace or if you watch Modern Family, if you watch Queer as Folk,

00:58:32.160 --> 00:58:35.920
[Guest]: then you get an idea of how it's a part of their culture, you know.

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:40.940
[Guest]: And since I was born in the 90s, right, so when I got to 2000s, the situation was much

00:58:40.940 --> 00:58:43.560
[Guest]: better for the queers around India.

00:58:43.560 --> 00:58:47.480
[Guest]: Like there were parties and there were associative events happening in scarcity.

00:58:47.480 --> 00:58:51.840
[Guest]: But now, because it's been like spoken about so much and like everybody wants to get on

00:58:51.840 --> 00:58:56.280
[Guest]: board this whole ship and be an ally and get on the bandwagon of, you know, being cool

00:58:56.280 --> 00:58:59.360
[Guest]: because you're pro-gay, it's very common now.

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:03.440
[Guest]: So it's not such a rarity as it was when I was like 17 or 18.

00:59:03.440 --> 00:59:08.520
[Guest]: Now I can go to a queer event every evening, every evening or every weekend almost now.

00:59:08.520 --> 00:59:10.960
[Guest]: So it's a pretty chill situation.

00:59:10.960 --> 00:59:11.960
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:59:11.960 --> 00:59:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you've been doing this very interesting show Keeping It Queer for quite

00:59:16.680 --> 00:59:17.680
[Amit Varma]: a long time.

00:59:17.680 --> 00:59:19.640
[Amit Varma]: I think your season two just got over.

00:59:19.640 --> 00:59:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And what you do in the show for my listeners, and I recommend to my listeners that they

00:59:22.840 --> 00:59:24.960
[Amit Varma]: check it out at IVMpodcast.com.

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Just look on the shows, look for Keeping It Queer.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:28.800
[Amit Varma]: It's a fantastic show.

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:33.600
[Amit Varma]: While doing the show, what are the sort of insights that you gained about what in a sense

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:36.080
[Guest]: was your community itself?

00:59:36.080 --> 00:59:42.160
[Guest]: I think that there's still a lot of sexism in the queer community itself, like it still

00:59:42.160 --> 00:59:46.440
[Guest]: becomes a man show at the end, so the gay men think that they're entitled in some way.

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:51.640
[Guest]: And so there's still a lot of like toxic masculinity and, you know, a lot of these behaviour within

00:59:51.640 --> 00:59:52.640
[Amit Varma]: the gay community.

00:59:52.640 --> 00:59:58.160
[Guest]: And like they look down upon lesbians and trans women who mainly are the foremost leaders

00:59:58.160 --> 00:59:59.920
[Guest]: in the community.

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:04.600
[Guest]: And I've really ended up, because when I was growing up also, like, you know, the sight

01:00:04.600 --> 01:00:08.840
[Guest]: of a trans person begging for money at the signal or in the train would scare me because

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:11.840
[Guest]: I was brought up in that kind of mentality.

01:00:11.840 --> 01:00:17.560
[Guest]: But the most humane touch that I've had, you know, the most humane interactions I've had

01:00:17.560 --> 01:00:20.600
[Guest]: after being a part of the community is with trans people and understanding their stories

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:23.360
[Guest]: has been like the most poignant moment in my life.

01:00:23.360 --> 01:00:27.680
[Guest]: Like I've spoken to so many people, not only on record on Keeping It Queer, but like in

01:00:27.680 --> 01:00:29.640
[Guest]: real life otherwise as well.

01:00:29.640 --> 01:00:33.760
[Guest]: Just the fact that they have gone through so much more than I could have ever gone makes

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:37.480
[Guest]: me understand the need for the struggle, the need for talking about it on a bigger platform

01:00:37.480 --> 01:00:41.840
[Guest]: and getting to normalise this conversation because they have just been mistreated everywhere,

01:00:41.840 --> 01:00:48.240
[Guest]: you know, like with jobs, with medical, healthcare, with their own families that thrown out, defined

01:00:48.240 --> 01:00:49.320
[Guest]: their own communities.

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:54.400
[Guest]: And despite people being aware that, you know, India comes from a very strong culturally

01:00:54.400 --> 01:00:58.200
[Guest]: heritage wise, we are very strong in terms of respecting our trans people.

01:00:58.200 --> 01:01:04.120
[Guest]: They were put in the uppermost rungs of like the King's Sabha.

01:01:04.120 --> 01:01:06.200
[Guest]: So like what happened and how did we go wrong?

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:11.120
[Guest]: And the understanding of that helped me empathise a lot more with the trans community of this

01:01:11.120 --> 01:01:12.120
[Amit Varma]: country.

01:01:12.120 --> 01:01:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And you were, of course, extremely fortunate, not just sort of in your background relatively,

01:01:16.680 --> 01:01:20.920
[Amit Varma]: but also that you had comedy in your art as an outlet to which you could turn writing

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:21.920
[Guest]: as an outlet.

01:01:21.920 --> 01:01:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of people don't have that and things are tough for them.

01:01:25.400 --> 01:01:29.520
[Amit Varma]: And through the course of doing this show, you speak spoken to so many different kinds

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:30.520
[Amit Varma]: of people.

01:01:30.520 --> 01:01:36.680
[Amit Varma]: At what level, for you, when you think about the struggle that your life involves, does

01:01:36.680 --> 01:01:40.480
[Amit Varma]: it involve not just a personal struggle of coming to terms with who you are and doing

01:01:40.480 --> 01:01:44.600
[Amit Varma]: what you have to do and the personal struggles of your art, but also this larger struggle

01:01:44.600 --> 01:01:51.960
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, you want to make India more progressive in this sense and sort of advance

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:53.840
[Guest]: the cause of the queer community as it were.

01:01:53.840 --> 01:01:54.840
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:01:54.840 --> 01:01:57.720
[Guest]: And also like to tell them that, hey, listen to these love stories of these people, you

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:00.360
[Guest]: know, people, when they come to my show, I don't tell them like, oh, we're going to be

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:01.360
[Guest]: preachy about this.

01:02:01.360 --> 01:02:02.840
[Guest]: Just tell me what happened in your life.

01:02:02.840 --> 01:02:04.320
[Guest]: So they'll be like, oh, I had a crush on this person.

01:02:04.320 --> 01:02:06.200
[Guest]: I was a girl and I had a crush on a girl.

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:07.440
[Guest]: And then she fell in love with me.

01:02:07.440 --> 01:02:11.960
[Guest]: And then we had the longest dating time, you know, and that makes me so happy because they're

01:02:11.960 --> 01:02:17.280
[Guest]: not pretending to be anybody else than who they are and telling me a story that would

01:02:17.280 --> 01:02:18.720
[Guest]: happen in anybody else's life.

01:02:18.720 --> 01:02:23.000
[Guest]: So the idea was always to create conversations which are still normalizing the whole idea

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:24.520
[Guest]: that we also have lives.

01:02:24.520 --> 01:02:29.320
[Guest]: It's just that we don't flash it too much because we're afraid that you won't like it.

01:02:29.320 --> 01:02:32.520
[Guest]: But maybe in this way, when you listen to our stories, you'll like it, you'll understand

01:02:32.520 --> 01:02:38.280
[Guest]: that we do come with a certain sense of fear because of how we are treated in society.

01:02:38.280 --> 01:02:41.280
[Guest]: So that's why we need all these stories to come out and say that there's a promise for

01:02:41.280 --> 01:02:45.320
[Guest]: a better tomorrow, even though it's going to be very rigorous and slow, we still have

01:02:45.320 --> 01:02:47.480
[Guest]: hope that it'll get just better.

01:02:47.480 --> 01:02:51.720
[Guest]: And that's what like last year's Pride was, it gets better, was the theme of the Pride.

01:02:51.720 --> 01:02:52.720
[Amit Varma]: That's a lovely line.

01:02:52.720 --> 01:02:53.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:57.200
[Guest]: So it was so amazing because I went to the Pride with my microphone and spoke to so many

01:02:57.200 --> 01:02:58.200
[Unknown]: people.

01:02:58.200 --> 01:03:02.080
[Guest]: So I did a queer edition for the Pride that year.

01:03:02.080 --> 01:03:08.600
[Guest]: And hence all these stories when I was setting out to put them together, it was like a audio

01:03:08.600 --> 01:03:11.320
[Amit Varma]: journal, so to say, of these stories.

01:03:11.320 --> 01:03:12.320
[Amit Varma]: And where is it?

01:03:12.320 --> 01:03:13.320
[Guest]: Where can people listen to this?

01:03:13.320 --> 01:03:14.320
[Guest]: It's on ivampodcast.com only.

01:03:14.320 --> 01:03:19.160
[Guest]: So it's like, so that's the whole idea that I want to have all these people who are out

01:03:19.160 --> 01:03:20.160
[Guest]: to talk about it.

01:03:20.160 --> 01:03:24.520
[Guest]: So when a kid looks up for it, when they're discovering queer identities and everything,

01:03:24.520 --> 01:03:28.440
[Guest]: they'll have some kind of research work to go back to, which is again, like a very Indian

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:32.600
[Guest]: voice, you know, because as I said, I went to men from around the world to understand

01:03:32.600 --> 01:03:34.040
[Guest]: what they went through.

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:37.800
[Guest]: But the situation is very differently perceived in India.

01:03:37.800 --> 01:03:42.800
[Guest]: So I wanted to give listeners a chance to understand the queer Indian identity from

01:03:42.800 --> 01:03:43.800
[Guest]: the podcast perspective.

01:03:43.800 --> 01:03:48.880
[Amit Varma]: Is there any of this happening in the languages itself or it's just sort of English?

01:03:48.880 --> 01:03:52.520
[Guest]: I do speak to people in Marathi and Hindi as well on the show.

01:03:52.520 --> 01:03:56.680
[Guest]: But like, again, my language skills are mostly stronger in English.

01:03:56.680 --> 01:03:57.960
[Guest]: So we stuck to that.

01:03:57.960 --> 01:04:02.440
[Guest]: But there's also like, a lot of insight into what's it like to come from different backgrounds

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:06.920
[Guest]: and have different identities also, from around the country that to like, you know, I've spoken

01:04:06.920 --> 01:04:15.040
[Guest]: to people on Skype and we had Alok Vaid Menon, they are a spoken word poet from America,

01:04:15.040 --> 01:04:21.800
[Guest]: femme and very proudly so, so, so they actually face a lot of homophobia in America when they

01:04:21.800 --> 01:04:23.020
[Guest]: walk on the streets.

01:04:23.020 --> 01:04:26.480
[Guest]: So it was important to get their story when they came down to India, I kind of found them

01:04:26.480 --> 01:04:29.960
[Guest]: and Shakti and Alok came and they did a great episode with me.

01:04:29.960 --> 01:04:35.640
[Guest]: So hence, I feel like, when you go back to understanding why you wanted to do this, there

01:04:35.640 --> 01:04:37.000
[Guest]: has to be a purpose to this, right?

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:40.940
[Guest]: So when we finally got all these stories, and I'd look back at it, and people find me

01:04:40.940 --> 01:04:43.840
[Guest]: online and message me saying that, hey, I heard your podcast, it helped me cope with

01:04:43.840 --> 01:04:44.840
[Guest]: so much.

01:04:44.840 --> 01:04:49.160
[Guest]: It means a lot to me eventually that I did not go on a on a save your mission at all.

01:04:49.160 --> 01:04:51.960
[Guest]: I was just like, I hope that someone did this for me.

01:04:51.960 --> 01:04:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's what I'm going to do for them.

01:04:52.960 --> 01:04:54.960
[Guest]: Had you heard something like this, when you were 15 or 16?

01:04:54.960 --> 01:04:58.840
